            <person xml:id="pers0247">
               <p>Bredin was a native of <placeName>Ireland</placeName>, serving as a Roman Catholic
                  schoolmaster and struggling with a drinking problem, when he was converted by a
                  Methodist preacher. He was admitted on trial as an <seg ana="itinerancy"
                     >itinerant</seg> preacher himself in <date when="1769">1769</date>, and given
                  full standing in <date when="1771">1771</date>, serving in
                     <placeName>Ireland</placeName>, <placeName>Scotland</placeName>,
                     <placeName>England</placeName>, and the <placeName>Channel Islands</placeName>.
                  During this time he was a frequent correspondent with <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>. Poor health forced Bredin to
                  retire in <date when="1792">1792</date>. See <hi rend="italic">Minutes</hi>
                  (post-Wesley, <date when="1820">1820</date>), 5:98; and Vickers, <hi rend="italic"
                     >Dictionary</hi>, 42.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
